\u25aa Left kick back lane when lit (saves the ball from draining)
\u25aa Ball save gate (returns ball to shooter) awards extra ball
\u25aa 3 pop bumpers

Additional features of Four Million B.C. include: 2 Zipper flippers, 3 Pop bumpers, 2 mushroom bumpers, 2 Slingshots, 2 Standup targets, 1 Kick-out hole, Multiball, Ball advance lane, Left outlane kicker, Ramp, Skill shot, Ball return gate, The kick-out hole has a motorized Flash Bonus for variable awards. Maximum displayed point score is 99,990 points per player. Replay wheel maximum: 25. Sound: 1 bell, knocker.

Pricing - Then & Now

Original (Street) Price: When first released in 2000, the dedicated arcade cabinet retailed around $4,500\u20134,900, based on listings from restored cabinet resellers  \ufffc

VintageArcade.net lists Gauntlet Legends at $4,495 with a $200 upgrade option for Dark Legacy (totaling ~ $4,695), and some show ~$4,895 as well  \ufffc

Collector/Resale Prices Today:

Standard restored units typically sell between $4,000\u20135,500. For instance, Gameroom Goodies lists a fully refurbished Dark Legacy cabinet at $4,495\ufffc.

Premium or rare cabinets, including original parts or pristine condition, may command upwards of $8,000\u201311,000. A non\u2011Arcade-specialist site listed one at ~$11,200 retail (discounted to $8,500), though this may be an outlier due to bundled services  \ufffc.

Private sales/auctions tend to land around $1,000\u20131,500 in local deals, especially when open to conversion boards or disclaimers on condition (). More rare finds have been reported around $4,500

At the time of purchase, the machine had been completely shopped, including replacing many of the older incandescent lighting with LEDs. All rubbers were replaced last year, a pinball specialist gave it a once over in December 2024, and the field was recently rewaxed. For an older (and more affordable) pinball game, Black Rose has so-ooo many different and unique elements and shots, that our family never got tired of it (our moving necessitates the sale). ads.author: Tom Grizzard
ads.title: 1978 Bally PLAYBOY pinball machine -New Playfield, new cabinet decals
ads.description:
Experience nostalgia with this classic 1978 Bally PLAYBOY pinball machine. This machine has been given a new lease of life with a brand new playfield and cabinet decals, making it the perfect addition to any arcade or pinball collection. The machine boasts the iconic PLAYBOY branding and provides endless hours of entertainment for all ages. Don't miss out on the chance to own this timeless piece of gaming history.

Notable Features:     Flippers (2), Pop bumpers (3), Slingshots (2), Standup targets (6), 5-bank drop targets (1), Star rollover (1), Upper left kickback lane (the Grotto).

The backglass depicts Hugh Hefner with 1976 Playmate Patti McGuire and 1977 Playmate Sondra Theodore. Tom Nieman, VP of Marketing for Bally Pinball, told us his name or initials appeared on most backglasses of this time period for which he obtained the license. On this game, his name appears on the champagne bottle.

The start-up tune, Grotto tune, and bonus score countdown tune resemble portions of Cy Coleman's "Playboy's Theme" from the 1969 TV show "Playboy After Dark". An article in the Spring 2019 issue of Playboy magazine about the "Singing Playmates" mentioned that their producer Vic Caesar "arranged the surprisingly famous theme to the Playboy pinball game."

Good condition. Everything works.

 
Will ship via freight carrier at buyer's expense... contact for quote.  Local delivery available for a nominal fee.
